# Project

lsb-shop — full-stack e-commerce platform for a clothing store.
Monorepo: `backend/` (Django 5.2 + DRF · Python 3.13.2) + `frontend/` (Next.js 15 · TypeScript 5)
Backend: Apps + Services Layer. Frontend: pure UI — no business logic, no DB.

# Architecture overview

```
backend/apps/
├── core/       → TimeStampedModel, SoftDeleteModel, exceptions, pagination, utils
├── users/      → User custom, Address, roles, auth
├── products/   → Product, Category, Variant, ProductImage
├── cart/       → Cart in Redis with TTL (no DB model)
├── orders/     → Order, OrderItem, OrderHistory, Return
└── payments/   → Stripe, webhooks, refunds
```

# App structure — every Django app has exactly these files

```
app/
├── models.py       → ORM only, no business logic
├── serializers.py  → input/output validation only, no logic
├── views.py        → ViewSets/APIView — orchestrate only, call services
├── urls.py         → router.register() or urlpatterns
├── services.py     → ALL business logic lives here, no HTTP context
├── selectors.py    → complex read queries only, no mutations
├── tasks.py        → Celery tasks for this domain
├── filters.py      → django-filter FilterSet classes
├── permissions.py  → custom DRF permission classes
├── admin.py        → django-unfold admin registration
└── tests/
    ├── conftest.py         → shared fixtures for this app
    ├── factories.py        → factory_boy factories
    ├── test_models.py
    ├── test_services.py    ← most important
    └── test_views.py       ← integration tests with APIClient
```

# Which view type to use — no exceptions

- **ModelViewSet** → any CRUD resource (Product, Order, User, Category, Cart)
- **@action on ViewSet** → sub-actions on a resource (archive, cancel, apply-coupon)
- **APIView** → non-resource endpoints only (login, checkout process, Stripe webhook)

Never put business logic in views. Views only: validate → call service → return response.

# services.py owns ALL business logic

```python
# CORRECT — view delegates everything to service
class OrderViewSet(viewsets.ModelViewSet):
    def create(self, request, *args, **kwargs):
        serializer = self.get_serializer(data=request.data)
        serializer.is_valid(raise_exception=True)
        order = OrderService.create_order(
            user=request.user,
            items=serializer.validated_data["items"],
        )
        return Response(OrderSerializer(order).data, status=201)

# WRONG — business logic in view
class OrderViewSet(viewsets.ModelViewSet):
    def create(self, request, *args, **kwargs):
        product = Product.objects.get(...)  # ← query in view
        if product.stock < qty:             # ← business rule in view
            return Response(...)
```

# N+1 queries — mandatory prevention

Always use `select_related` (ForeignKey/OneToOne) and `prefetch_related` (ManyToMany/reverse FK) in selectors. Never return a queryset that will cause N+1 in the serializer.

```python
# CORRECT
def get_orders_for_user(user_id: int) -> QuerySet[Order]:
    return (
        Order.objects.filter(user_id=user_id)
        .select_related("user")
        .prefetch_related("items__product__images")
        .order_by("-created_at")
    )

# WRONG — N+1: 1 query for orders + 1 per order for items
def get_orders_for_user(user_id: int) -> QuerySet[Order]:
    return Order.objects.filter(user_id=user_id)
```

Check django-debug-toolbar in dev — it highlights N+1 queries automatically.

# select_for_update — mandatory for stock and numeric mutations

```python
# Any read-then-modify on a quantity MUST use select_for_update
@transaction.atomic
def reserve_stock(product_id: int, quantity: int) -> None:
    # Locks the row until transaction ends — prevents race conditions
    product = Product.objects.select_for_update().get(id=product_id)
    if product.stock < quantity:
        raise InsufficientStock(product.name)
    product.stock -= quantity
    product.save()
```

# Cache invalidation — invalidate on write, always in service layer

```python
# Define cache key constants
PRODUCT_LIST_PATTERN = "products:list:*"
PRODUCT_DETAIL_KEY = "products:detail:{product_id}"
CART_KEY = "cart:{user_id}"  # TTL 7 days

class ProductService:
    @staticmethod
    def update_product(product_id: int, data: dict) -> Product:
        product = Product.objects.get(id=product_id)
        for key, value in data.items():
            setattr(product, key, value)
        product.save()
        cache.delete_pattern(PRODUCT_LIST_PATTERN)
        cache.delete(PRODUCT_DETAIL_KEY.format(product_id=product_id))
        log.info("product.updated", product_id=product_id)
        return product
```

# Logging — structlog always, include relevant context

```python
import structlog
log = structlog.get_logger()

log.info("order.created", user_id=user.id, order_id=order.id, total=str(order.total))
log.info("cart.item.added", user_id=user_id, product_id=product_id, quantity=quantity)
log.warning("stock.low", product_id=product.id, stock=product.stock)
log.error("payment.failed", user_id=user.id, order_id=order.id, error=str(e))

# NEVER log: passwords, tokens, card numbers, email content, personal data
```

# Exceptions — custom hierarchy, never expose technical errors

```python
# apps/core/exceptions.py
class ShopError(Exception):
    status_code: int = 500
    default_message: str = "Ha ocurrido un error. Inténtalo de nuevo."

class InsufficientStock(ShopError):
    status_code = 400
    def __init__(self, product_name: str) -> None:
        self.default_message = f"Stock insuficiente para '{product_name}'."

class ResourceNotFound(ShopError):
    status_code = 404
    default_message = "El recurso solicitado no existe."

class PaymentFailed(ShopError):
    status_code = 402
    default_message = "El pago no pudo procesarse. Verifica tus datos."

class PermissionDenied(ShopError):
    status_code = 403
    default_message = "No tienes permisos para realizar esta acción."

class CartExpired(ShopError):
    status_code = 400
    default_message = "Tu carrito ha expirado. Por favor agrégalo de nuevo."
```

Never let Django ORM, Redis, or Stripe exceptions reach the user.

# pyproject.toml — single config file for all tools

All tool config lives in `backend/pyproject.toml`. Never create separate `.flake8`, `mypy.ini`, or `bandit.yaml`.

# API URL structure — always /api/v1/ prefix

```
/api/v1/auth/login/                 /api/v1/products/
/api/v1/auth/register/              /api/v1/products/{id}/
/api/v1/auth/token/refresh/         /api/v1/products/{id}/archive/
/api/v1/auth/logout/                /api/v1/products/categories/
/api/v1/auth/google/                /api/v1/cart/
/api/v1/users/me/                   /api/v1/cart/items/
/api/v1/orders/                     /api/v1/payments/webhook/stripe/
/api/v1/orders/{id}/cancel/         /api/v1/admin/stats/   /api/v1/admin/orders/…
/health/                            /api/docs/  /api/redoc/
```
(Categorías y presets viven bajo el prefijo **`/api/v1/products/`** — ver `apps/products/urls.py`.)

# Code standards — Python

- Python 3.13 syntax · full type hints on every function · mypy strict must pass
- `type: ignore` only with comment explaining why
- Absolute imports always (`from apps.products.models import Product`)
- `uv` only — never bare `pip`
- Naming: files/folders `snake_case` · classes `PascalCase` · constants `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`

# Code standards — TypeScript / Next.js

- TypeScript strict — no `any` without comment
- `app/` contains ONLY routing files: `page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`
- Components in `features/{domain}/components/` — never inside `app/`
- No business logic, no Prisma, no Server Actions with business logic, no NextAuth
- All API calls via `lib/api/` functions, organized per domain (`index.ts` client, `server.ts` RSC, `mappers.ts` for shared DRF→app types — do not duplicate mapping). When editing `frontend/lib/api/` or `frontend/types/`, follow `.cursor/rules/frontend-api-dry.mdc` for DRY (extract mappers/helpers only when a second identical use exists or is added).
- RSC session check: `import { auth } from "@/lib/api/auth/server"` only
- Zustand for UI state only (modals, sheets) — never server state

# Agent autonomy

May run without asking:
- `uv run pytest` · `uv run ruff check .` · `uv run ruff format .` · `uv run mypy apps/`
- `python manage.py check` · `python manage.py showmigrations`
- Any read: cat, view, ls, tree, grep, find, git status, git log

Must always ask before:
- `git commit` or `git push`
- Creating or modifying any file
- `python manage.py migrate` or `makemigrations`
- Any destructive operation (delete, drop table, migration downgrade)
- Opening or modifying a PR
